I've read the argument in Rudin, but I think I need a little clarification \begin{align}
e^a e^b &= \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{a^k}{k!} \sum_{m=0}^{\infty} \frac{b^m}{m!}\\ &= \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \frac{ n!}{n!}  \sum_{k=0}^{n} \frac{a^k}{k!} \frac{b^{n-k}}{(n-k)!} \\
&= \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \frac{(a+b)^n}{n!}\\
&=e^{a+b}\\
\end{align} I'd like to understand how we get from the first line to the second. Of course $m =n-k$, but how do we ensure that we haven't missed any addends in the limit changing process? Changing limits: $m=0 \rightarrow n-k=0 \rightarrow k=n$ and $m=\infty \rightarrow n-k=\infty \rightarrow k=0$, assuming $n \to \infty$. \begin{align}
\frac{b^m}{m!} \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{a^k}{k!} 
&= \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{a^k}{k!} \frac{b^{m}}{m!} \\
&=\sum_{k=0}^{?} \frac{a^k}{k!} \frac{b^{n-k}}{(n-k)!} \\
\end{align} how to justify that "?"$=n$ ?

